# Our Setup, Import Libaries, Create our Imshow Function and Download our Images
import cv2
import numpy as np
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt

# Define our imshow function 
def imshow(title = "Image", image = None, size = 10):
    w, h = image.shape[0], image.shape[1]
    aspect_ratio = w/h
    plt.figure(figsize=(size * aspect_ratio,size))
    plt.imshow(cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB))
    plt.title(title)
    plt.show()

1. Line Detection - Hough Lines¶

The Hough transform takes a binary edge map as input and attempts to locate edges placed as straight lines. The idea of the Hough transform is, that every edge point in the edge map is transformed to all possible lines that could pass through that point.

cv2.HoughLines(binarized/thresholded image, 𝜌 accuracy, 𝜃 accuracy, threshold)

  • Threshold here is the minimum vote for it to be considered a line
In [22]:
image = cv2.imread('Datasets/images/soduku.jpg')
imshow('Original', image)

# Grayscale and Canny Edges extracted
gray = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
edges = cv2.Canny(gray, 100, 170, apertureSize = 3)
imshow('edge', edges)

# Run HoughLines using a rho accuracy of 1 pixel
# theta accuracy of np.pi / 180 which is 1 degree. Odatda 140
# Our line threshold is set to 240 (number of points on line)
lines = cv2.HoughLines(edges, rho=1, theta=np.pi / 180, threshold=240) 
# We iterate through each line and convert it to the format
# required by cv2.lines (i.e. requiring end points)

#kodlarga kop kirishmasdan x,y start va end pointlarni ajratib olish
for line in lines:
    rho, theta = line[0] 
    a = np.cos(theta)
    b = np.sin(theta)
    x0 = a * rho
    y0 = b * rho
    x1 = int(x0 + 1000 * (-b))
    y1 = int(y0 + 1000 * (a))
    x2 = int(x0 - 1000 * (-b))
    y2 = int(y0 - 1000 * (a))
    cv2.line(image, (x1, y1), (x2, y2), (255, 0, 0), 2)
    
imshow('Hough Lines', image)

2. Probabilistic Hough Lines - Hough linesdan osonroq va compututionally expensive bo'lmagan method¶

A Hough Transform is considered probabilistic if it uses random sampling of the edge points. These algorithms can be divided based on how they map image space to parameter space.

cv2.HoughLinesP(binarized image, 𝜌 accuracy, 𝜃 accuracy, threshold, minimum line length, max line gap)
In [35]:
# Grayscale and Canny Edges extracted
image = cv2.imread('Datasets/images/soduku.jpg')
gray = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
edges = cv2.Canny(gray, 100, 170, apertureSize = 3)

imshow('original', image)
imshow('edge', edges) 

# rho(pixel) - bu tog'ri chiziqni og'ishi pixeli odatda 1 ga teng boladi. Yani togri chiziq tekis pixelda yotmaydi. 
# qanchadur og'gan bo'lsa uni berib ketish kerak. 
# theta(gradus) - og'ish gradusi. np.pi/180 - 1 gradus ga teng
# threshold - chegarasi. number of points in lines. yani necha pixelgacha chiziqlar chizilsin
# minLineLength - eng kami necha pixel min Line chizsin 
# maxLineGap - Max ruxsat etilgan boshliq pointlar orasida. 

lines = cv2.HoughLinesP(edges, rho=1, theta=np.pi / 180, threshold=180, minLineLength=3, maxLineGap=30) #x,y, x2,y2 qaytaradi
print(lines.shape)

for line in lines:
    for x1,y1,x2,y2 in line:
        cv2.line(image,(x1,y1), (x2,y2),(0,255,0),1)

imshow('Probabilistic Hough Lines', image)

(59, 1, 4)

3.Circle Detection - Hough Cirlces¶

cv2.HoughCircles(image, method, dp, MinDist, param1, param2, minRadius, MaxRadius)

  • Method - currently only cv2.HOUGH_GRADIENT available
  • dp - Inverse ratio of accumulator resolution
  • MinDist - the minimum distance between the center of detected circles
  • param1 - Gradient value used in the edge detection
  • param2 - Accumulator threshold for the HOUGH_GRADIENT method (lower allows more circles to be detected (false positives))
  • minRadius - limits the smallest circle to this size (via radius)

  • MaxRadius - similarly sets the limit for the largest circles

  • HoughCircles(rasm(blur bolgan), cv2.HOUGH_GRADIENT, rho=1, minDist, param1,param2,minRadius, maxRadius)

  • rasm albatta Gaussian blur bolishi kerak.
  • rho - bu ogish pixeli odatda 1,
  • minDist - bu aylanalar orasidagi minimum distansiya
  • param1 -
  • param2-
  • minRadius - eng kichik min radius
  • maxRadius - eng kotta max radius
In [40]:
image = cv2.imread('Datasets/images/Circles_Packed_In_Square_11.jpeg')
imshow('Circles', image)
gray = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)

blur = cv2.medianBlur(gray, 5)
imshow("Gray Blurred image", blur)

circles = cv2.HoughCircles(blur, cv2.HOUGH_GRADIENT, 1.2, 25)
circles = np.uint16(np.around(circles)) #chizigimiz float qaytaradi integerga otkazib olamiz 

#chiziq 3 ta indexli royxat qaytaradi. 0 va 1 index center, 2 index bu radius.
for i in circles[0,:]: #3d matrix bolgani uchun uni ichini olamiz va loopga solamiz. 
    
    # draw the outer circle
    cv2.circle(image,(i[0], i[1]), i[2], (0, 0, 255), 5)
    
    # draw the center of the circle
    cv2.circle(image, (i[0], i[1]), 2, (0, 0, 255), 8)

imshow('Detected circles', image)

4.Blob Detection - blob bu interestina area or group of segment of pixel that we are interesting¶

The function cv2.drawKeypoints takes the following arguments:

cv2.drawKeypoints(input image, keypoints, blank_output_array, color, flags)

flags:

  • cv2.DRAW_MATCHES_FLAGS_DEFAULT
  • cv2.DRAW_MATCHES_FLAGS_DRAW_RICH_KEYPOINTS
  • cv2.DRAW_MATCHES_FLAGS_DRAW_OVER_OUTIMG
  • cv2.DRAW_MATCHES_FLAGS_NOT_DRAW_SINGLE_POINTS
In [43]:
# Read image
image = cv2.imread("Datasets/images/Sunflowers.jpg")
imshow("Original", image)

# Set up the detector with default parameters.
detector = cv2.SimpleBlobDetector_create()
 
# Detect blobs.
keypoints = detector.detect(image)
 
# Draw detected blobs as red circles.
# cv2.DRAW_MATCHES_FLAGS_DRAW_RICH_KEYPOINTS ensures the size of
# the circle corresponds to the size of blob
blank = np.zeros((1,1)) 
blobs = cv2.drawKeypoints(image, keypoints, blank, (0,255,0),
                                      cv2.DRAW_MATCHES_FLAGS_DEFAULT)
 
# Show keypoints
imshow("Blobs", blobs)
